Yes, because for each j in Fortran's loop (which corresponds to Java's i in 1..n-1), the modinv argument is (Java's i+1) which is (j) in Fortran's index. Because Java's i starts at 1, j in Fortran starts at 2 (since j=2 is the first step after the initial q(1) = 1). So that part is handled. Then, the main loop in Java:

for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
    long val = q[i] + q[n - i - 1] - 1;
    val *= a[i];
    val %= mod;
    val *= p;
    val %= mod;
    ans += val;
    ans %= mod;
} In Fortran, since the arrays are 1-based, the loop will run from i=1 to i=n.

The Java code uses a loop-based extended Euclidean algorithm. So in Fortran, the function modinv(a, m) would return the modular inverse of a mod m. Let's implement that. The function in Java:

static long modinv(long a, int m) {
    long b = m;
    long u = 1;
    long v = 0;
    long tmp = 0;
    while (b > 0) {
        long t = a / b;
        a -= t * b;
        tmp = a; a = b; b = tmp;
        u -= t * v;
        tmp = u; u = v; v = tmp;
    }
    u %= m;
    if (u < 0) u += m;
    return u;
} In Fortran, since we need to handle 64-bit integers (since Java uses long), but Fortran's integers can be 32 or 64-bit, depending on the compiler. To avoid overflow, perhaps use integer(kind=8) variables. So variables a, b, u, v, tmp, t should be 64-bit integers. So the Fortran function:

function modinv(a, m) result(res)
    integer(kind=8), intent(in) :: a, m
    integer(kind=8) :: res
    integer(kind=8) :: b, u, v, tmp, t, a0, b0

    a0 = a
    b0 = m
    u = 1_8
    v = 0_8

    b = b0

    do while (b > 0)
        t = a0 / b
        a0 = a0 - t * b
        tmp = a0
        a0 = b
        b = tmp

        u = u - t * v
        tmp = u
        u = v
        v = tmp
    end do

    u = modulo(u, m) if (u < 0) u = u + m

    res = u
end function

Wait, but in Fortran, the variables inside the function need to handle the input a and m. Also, note that in Java, the parameters are (a, m), and the code modifies a and b (which starts as m). So in the function, a and b are copies. So in Fortran, the parameters are a and m, and variables a0 and b0 are initialized to a and m, then modified. But wait, in Java, a is a long passed into modinv.

Then, during the loop, a0 and b are modified. Wait, let's see:

Java's code starts with:

long b = m;
long u = 1;
long v = 0;
long tmp = 0;
while (b > 0) {
    long t = a / b;
    a -= t * b;
    tmp = a; a = b; b = tmp; u -= t * v;
    tmp = u; u = v; v = tmp;
}

So in Fortran, the initial a is a (the input), and b is m.
